AFRICAN SWINE FEVER - EUROPE (65): BELGIUM (LUXEMBOURG) WILD BOAR, SPREAD, FRANCE ALERTNESS
*******************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 22 Dec 2018
Source: L'est Republicain [in French, trans. Corr. SB, summarized, edited]
https://www.estrepublicain.fr/edition-de-verdun/2018/12/22/peste-porcine-un-sanglier-contamine-en-belgique-a-la-frontiere-de-la-meuse-et-10


In Meix-devant-Virton, a Belgian border town not far from Thonne-La-Long [northeastern France], 10 carcasses of wild boar were found on Thursday [20 Dec 2018] on the Belgian side behind the installed fences in the so-called peripheral zone in front of a container park.

On Monday [17 Dec 2018], another carcass was found not far from Gerouville [northwest of Meix-devant-Virton, 1.5 km [0.93 miles] from the French border]. This carcass was tested and found positive for African swine fever [ASF] virus. On site, we realize that the erected fence will not stop ASF from crossing into France, especially as this area is interspersed with roads of the Walloon automobile network and forest roads in Macadam.

The test results of the 10 wild boar carcasses found in Meix-Devant-Virton are pending, but there is little doubt about the results. The distance between their site in Meix-devant-Virton and the French commune Thonne La-Long is 5.5 km [3.42 miles] as the crow flies. Its further advance into France's territory seems to be just a question of time.

Activities in the forest [in Belgium] are at a standstill. There are many other inherent issues, such as logging and the skidding of wood, which is now prohibited in the forest, with a consequent loss of profit of 400 000 euro [USD 456 000] just for the commune of Meix-Devant-Virton.

--
Communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview English Longhorns, Gut Laach
D-52385 Nideggen, Germany
