[The advance of ASF westwards from Zone II (the infected zone), composed of the Core Zone and Buffer Zone, into the peripheral (surveillance) Zone I (south) should be of serious concern to France. The zoning system of the affected territory in southern Belgium is presented in slide 5 of Belgium's recent (19 Dec 2018) presentation at https://ec.europa.eu/food/sites/food/files/animals/docs/ad_control-measures_asf_conf-20181219_pres-06.pdf. Subscribers are referred to the explanatory comments in ProMED posting 20181221.6217892.

Meix-Devant-Virton (in Belgium) and, to its southwest, Thonne-La-Long (in France), are presented on the map at https://tinyurl.com/y8a6b6k4.

The measures undertaken by France to prevent the introduction of ASF-infected wild boar from Belgium by fencing and other activities, involving hunters, and to discover the disease as early as possible if/when introduced by passive and active surveillance, were described in the report of a Mission of the EU Veterinary Emergency Team (EUVET) to France (17-19 Oct 2018), presented in Brussels to the PAFF committee on 23 Nov 2018, available at https://ec.europa.eu/food/sites/food/files/animals/docs/reg-com_ahw_20181123_asf-euvet_fra.pdf. - Mod.AS

HealthMap/ProMED maps available at:
